{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Open your web browser and go to `git-scm.com`. This site usually detects your operating system automatically and highlights the correct version for your computer on the homepage.",
      "title": "Visit the Official Git Website"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click the **Download** button for your OS. On Windows, select the **64-bit Git for Windows Setup**. On macOS, you may be directed to a page with several options; choose the binary installer if you don't use a package manager.",
      "title": "Download the Installer"
    },
    {
      "text": "Open your Downloads folder and double-click the installer file. If your computer asks for permission to run the file or make changes, click **Yes** or **Allow** to proceed.",
      "title": "Run the Setup File"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click **Next** through the configuration screens. The default settings are recommended for most users. When you reach the final screen, click **Install** and wait for the progress bar to finish.",
      "title": "Follow the Installation Wizard"
    },
    {
      "text": "On Windows, search for and open **Command Prompt** or **PowerShell**. On macOS, open **Terminal** from your Applications folder. This is where you will interact with Git.",
      "title": "Open Your Terminal"
    },
    {
      "text": "Type `git --version` and press Enter. If the installation was successful, you will see a response similar to `git version 2.x.x`. If you see an 'ordered not found' error, try restarting your terminal.",
      "title": "Verify the Installation"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Park your vehicle on a flat, level surface away from traffic. Firmly engage the **parking brake** to prevent the car from rolling while it is lifted.",
      "title": "Secure the Vehicle"
    },
    {
      "text": "Use the lug wrench to turn each nut counter-clockwise (lefty-loosey). Only loosen them about half a turn. **Do not remove them yet**; the car's weight helps keep the wheel from spinning.",
      "title": "Loosen the Lug Nuts"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place the jack under the vehicle's frame at the designated jacking point near the flat tire. Refer to your owner's manual if you are unsure of the correct spot to avoid damaging the car.",
      "title": "Position the Jack"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn the jack handle clockwise to lift the vehicle. Continue until the flat tire is approximately **3 inches** off the ground and can spin freely without touching the pavement.",
      "title": "Raise the Vehicle"
    },
    {
      "text": "Unscrew the loosened lug nuts completely by hand. Place them in a secure location, like a pocket or the vehicle's interior, so they do not roll away or get lost in the dirt.",
      "title": "Remove the Lug Nuts"
    },
    {
      "text": "Grasp the tire with both hands and pull it straight toward you to slide it off the threaded studs. Lay the flat tire on its side under the edge of the vehicle for added safety while you work.",
      "title": "Pull Off the Flat Tire"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Gather your French press, a kettle, fresh coffee beans, and a grinder. Ensure the French press carafe is clean and the plunger moves smoothly.",
      "title": "Gather Your Supplies"
    },
    {
      "text": "Measure out 30 grams of coffee beans, which is roughly 3 to 4 level tablespoons. This amount is ideal for a standard 17-ounce (500ml) French press.",
      "title": "Measure the Coffee"
    },
    {
      "text": "Grind the beans to a **coarse** consistency, similar to the texture of sea salt. Avoid fine grinds, as they will clog the filter and make the coffee bitter.",
      "title": "Grind the Beans"
    },
    {
      "text": "Heat your water to approximately \\(200^\\circ F\\) (\\(93^\\circ C\\)). If you don't have a thermometer, bring the water to a boil and let it sit for 30 seconds before pouring.",
      "title": "Heat the Water"
    },
    {
      "text": "Remove the lid from the French press and pour your coarse coffee grounds into the bottom of the glass carafe.",
      "title": "Add Coffee to the Press"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour just enough hot water over the grounds to wet them completely. Wait 30 seconds; you should see the coffee rise and bubble—this is the \"bloom.\"",
      "title": "Bloom the Grounds"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour the remaining water into the carafe, filling it to about an inch below the rim. Ensure all coffee grounds are fully submerged.",
      "title": "Fill the Carafe"
    },
    {
      "text": "Gently stir the top layer with a spoon to break up the \"crust\" of floating grounds. Place the lid on top with the plunger pulled all the way up to trap the heat.",
      "title": "Stir and Seal"
    },
    {
      "text": "Set a timer and let the coffee steep for **4 minutes**. Do not plunge early, as the flavor needs this time to develop fully.",
      "title": "Wait Four Minutes"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press the plunger down slowly and with steady, even pressure. If the plunger becomes difficult to push, lift it up an inch and then continue downward.",
      "title": "Plunge Slowly"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour the coffee into your mug immediately. Leaving the coffee in the press after plunging will cause it to over-extract and become unpleasantly bitter.",
      "title": "Pour and Serve"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Collect a garden fork, a steel rake, and a bag of organic compost. Ensure you have enough compost to cover the entire garden bed to a depth of 2 to 3 inches before you begin.",
      "title": "Gather Your Tools and Materials"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pull out any visible weeds by the roots and remove large stones or old plant debris. The soil surface should be clear of any obstructions so you can work the ground easily.",
      "title": "Clear the Planting Area"
    },
    {
      "text": "Push your garden fork 8 to 10 inches deep into the soil. Rock the fork back and forth to create air pockets, then repeat this every few inches across the entire bed to break up compaction.",
      "title": "Loosen the Soil"
    },
    {
      "text": "Spread a 2 to 3-inch layer of organic compost evenly over the top of the loosened soil. You should see a consistent dark layer covering the entire planting zone.",
      "title": "Apply a Layer of Compost"
    },
    {
      "text": "Use the garden fork to turn the compost into the top 6 inches of soil. Mix until the compost is thoroughly integrated and you see a uniform, crumbly texture.",
      "title": "Mix Compost into the Soil"
    },
    {
      "text": "Draw a steel rake across the surface to break up any remaining large soil clods. Smooth the area until the bed is level and the soil particles are fine and even.",
      "title": "Rake the Surface Level"
    },
    {
      "text": "Lightly spray the garden bed with a hose until the soil is moist but not muddy. The soil should feel damp to the touch, indicating it is conditioned and ready for tomato seedlings.",
      "title": "Water the Prepared Bed"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Use a dry iron to remove all wrinkles from your fabric. Wrinkles can lead to inaccurate measurements and uneven edges. Lay the fabric completely flat on your cutting surface once it is smooth.",
      "title": "Iron the Fabric"
    },
    {
      "text": "Fold your fabric in half, matching the factory-finished edges called the selvages. Smooth the fabric until there are no diagonal ripples, which confirms the fabric grain is perfectly straight.",
      "title": "Align the Selvages"
    },
    {
      "text": "Use a quilting ruler and tailor's chalk to mark a rectangle measuring \\(27 \\times 40\\) inches. Ensure the corners are square by aligning the ruler's grid lines with the folded edge of the fabric.",
      "title": "Mark the Main Body Piece"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place sewing pins every 4 inches along the inside of your chalk lines through both layers of fabric. This prevents the layers from sliding or shifting while you are cutting.",
      "title": "Pin the Layers Together"
    },
    {
      "text": "Use fabric shears to cut exactly along your marked chalk lines. Keep the bottom blade of the scissors in contact with the table surface to maintain a stable, straight line.",
      "title": "Cut the Main Piece"
    },
    {
      "text": "On your remaining fabric, mark a second rectangle measuring \\(10 \\times 40\\) inches for the cuff. The \\(40\\)-inch width should be identical to the width of your first piece.",
      "title": "Mark the Cuff Piece"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pin the cuff layers together and cut along the chalk lines. You should now have two separate rectangles: the large main body and the smaller cuff piece.",
      "title": "Cut the Cuff Piece"
    },
    {
      "text": "Lay the cuff piece on top of the main body piece. The short edges of both pieces should line up perfectly. You are now ready to begin pinning for assembly.",
      "title": "Verify the Alignment"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Turn on your electronic tuner or open a tuning app on your phone. If you are using a clip-on tuner, attach it firmly to the guitar's headstock.",
      "title": "Prepare Your Tuner"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the thickest string. If the tuner shows it is low (flat), turn the peg to tighten it. If it is high (sharp), loosen it. Adjust until the tuner displays a green `E`.",
      "title": "Tune the 6th String (E)"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the next string down. Turn the corresponding tuning peg until the tuner indicates `A`. Always try to tune 'up' into the note for better tuning stability.",
      "title": "Tune the 5th String (A)"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 4th string. Adjust the tuning peg until the display centers on `D`. If you overshoot the note, loosen the string and tighten it back up to the pitch.",
      "title": "Tune the 4th String (D)"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 3rd string. Rotate the tuning peg until the tuner identifies the note as `G`. Ensure the needle or indicator light stays centered.",
      "title": "Tune the 3rd String (G)"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 2nd string. Carefully adjust the peg until the tuner reads `B`. This string is thinner, so make small, incremental turns.",
      "title": "Tune the 2nd String (B)"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the thinnest string. Turn the peg until the tuner displays `E`. Watch the screen closely to avoid over-tightening this fragile string.",
      "title": "Tune the 1st String (High E)"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck every string one last time from top to bottom. Tuning one string can sometimes shift the tension on others. When all six strings show green on your tuner, you are ready to play.",
      "title": "Verify All Strings"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Rotate the mode dial on top of your camera to the **M** position. This allows you to manually adjust the aperture, shutter speed, and ISO independently. Ensure your camera is turned on and the lens cap is removed.",
      "title": "Set Camera to Manual Mode"
    },
    {
      "text": "Use the primary control dial to change the aperture value. Look for a number preceded by an `f`, such as `f/4` or `f/8`. Lower numbers open the lens wider, allowing more light to reach the sensor while creating a shallower depth of field.",
      "title": "Adjust the Aperture (f-stop)"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn the secondary dial to change the shutter speed, displayed as a fraction like `1/200`. A slower speed (e.g., `1/60`) lets in more light but may cause blur if the camera moves. Higher speeds freeze motion but require more light.",
      "title": "Set the Shutter Speed"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press the **ISO** button and rotate the dial to select a value. Choose a low number like `100` for bright outdoor light or a higher number like `1600` for low-light indoor settings to increase the sensor's sensitivity to light.",
      "title": "Configure the ISO"
    },
    {
      "text": "Look at the scale at the bottom of your viewfinder or LCD screen. Adjust your settings until the indicator sits at the `0` mark. If it moves toward the `+` side, your photo will be brighter; toward the `-` side means the photo will be darker.",
      "title": "Center the Exposure Meter"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press the shutter button fully to take a photo. Press the **Playback** button to view the result. If the image looks too dark or washed out, tweak your settings based on the meter and repeat the process until satisfied.",
      "title": "Take and Review a Test Shot"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart. Point your toes slightly outward, about 5 to 20 degrees, to help with hip mobility. Ensure your weight is evenly distributed across your feet.",
      "title": "Set Your Stance"
    },
    {
      "text": "Tighten your abdominal muscles as if preparing for a nudge. Extend your arms straight out in front of you at shoulder height to provide a counterweight for balance.",
      "title": "Engage Your Core and Arms"
    },
    {
      "text": "Begin the movement by pushing your hips back as if you are about to sit in an invisible chair. Keep your weight centered on your heels and the mid-foot to avoid leaning too far forward.",
      "title": "Hinge at the Hips"
    },
    {
      "text": "Bend your knees and lower your body while keeping your **chest up** and your **back straight**. Continue lowering until your thighs are at least parallel to the floor.",
      "title": "Lower Your Body"
    },
    {
      "text": "Look down briefly; your knees should be tracking in line with your toes, not caving inward. You should feel significant tension in your glutes and quads if done correctly.",
      "title": "Check Knee Alignment"
    },
    {
      "text": "Drive through your heels to return to a standing position. Squeeze your **glutes** at the top of the movement to fully extend your hips and complete the repetition.",
      "title": "Drive Upward"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Em uma tigela pequena, misture `10g` de fermento biológico seco, `250ml` de água morna e uma pitada de açúcar. A água deve estar morna ao toque, não quente, para não matar o fermento.",
      "title": "Ative o Fermento"
    },
    {
      "text": "Deixe a mistura descansar por cerca de 10 minutos. Você saberá que o fermento está ativo quando notar uma camada de espuma cremosa e pequenas bolhas subindo à superfície.",
      "title": "Aguarde a Ativação"
    },
    {
      "text": "Em uma tigela grande, coloque `500g` de farinha de trigo e `10g` de sal. Misture bem com as mãos ou um batedor para distribuir o sal uniformemente.",
      "title": "Misture os Secos"
    },
    {
      "text": "Faça um buraco no centro da farinha e despeje a mistura de fermento. Use uma colher de pau para misturar do centro para fora, incorporando a farinha até formar uma massa rústica e pesada.",
      "title": "Incorpore os Líquidos"
    },
    {
      "text": "Transfira a massa para uma bancada limpa e levemente enfarinhada. Use a base da palma da mão para empurrar a massa para longe de você, dobre-a de volta e gire-a 90 graus.",
      "title": "Inicie a Sova"
    },
    {
      "text": "Continue o movimento de sova por aproximadamente 10 minutos. A massa deve deixar de ser pegajosa e irregular para se tornar lisa, macia e muito elástica.",
      "title": "Desenvolva o Glúten"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pressione a massa firmemente com o polegar. Ela deve ser elástica o suficiente para voltar lentamente e preencher o buraco. Se a marca permanecer, sove por mais 2 minutos.",
      "title": "Verifique o Ponto"
    },
    {
      "text": "Forme uma bola lisa com a massa, tensionando a superfície. Coloque-a em uma tigela levemente untada com um fio de óleo e cubra com um pano úmido para a primeira fermentação.",
      "title": "Prepare para o Descanso"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Localiza las llaves de paso debajo del fregadero y gíralas hacia la derecha hasta que se detengan. Abre el grifo para confirmar que no sale agua y liberar la presión acumulada.",
      "title": "Cierra el suministro de agua"
    },
    {
      "text": "Coloca un tapón o un trapo sobre el desagüe. Esto evitará que piezas pequeñas o tornillos caigan accidentalmente por la tubería mientras desarmas el grifo.",
      "title": "Protege el desagüe"
    },
    {
      "text": "Usa un destornillador plano para hacer palanca suavemente en la tapa decorativa del mango (la que indica Frío o Caliente). Debajo encontrarás el tornillo que sujeta la manija.",
      "title": "Retira la tapa del mango"
    },
    {
      "text": "Usa un destornillador de cruz para aflojar el tornillo central. Sujeta el mango y tira de él hacia arriba con firmeza para separarlo del cuerpo del grifo.",
      "title": "Desmonta el mango"
    },
    {
      "text": "Usa una llave inglesa para aflojar la tuerca de metal que sujeta el mecanismo interno. Gírala en sentido antihorario hasta que puedas retirarla con la mano.",
      "title": "Quita la tuerca de empaque"
    },
    {
      "text": "Tira del vástago o cartucho hacia arriba para extraerlo. Si está muy apretado, usa unas pinzas. Inspecciona la arandela de caucho en la base; si está rota o aplanada, debe ser reemplazada.",
      "title": "Extrae el vástago o cartucho"
    },
    {
      "text": "Inserta el nuevo cartucho o la arandela de repuesto. Asegúrate de que las muescas de la pieza coincidan exactamente con las ranuras dentro del grifo para un sellado perfecto.",
      "title": "Instala los repuestos"
    },
    {
      "text": "Vuelve a colocar la tuerca de empaque y apriétala con la llave. Coloca el mango, ajusta su tornillo y presiona la tapa decorativa hasta que encaje en su sitio.",
      "title": "Reensambla el grifo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Gira las llaves de paso hacia la izquierda para abrir el agua. Abre el grifo un momento y ciérralo; si no hay fugas en la base ni goteo en la salida, la reparación ha sido un éxito.",
      "title": "Prueba tu reparación"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Click the **File** tab in the top-left corner of the application window. This opens the backstage menu where you manage file-level actions.",
      "title": "Open the File Menu"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click **Save** in the left-hand sidebar. If this is a new document, the application will automatically prompt you to choose a location using the **Save As** screen.",
      "title": "Select the Save Command"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click **Browse** or select a folder like **Documents**. A window will appear showing the folders on your computer where you can store the file.",
      "title": "Choose a Storage Location"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click inside the **File name** box and type a descriptive name for your work, such as `Meeting_Notes`. Avoid using special characters like `/` or `?`.",
      "title": "Name Your Document"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click the **Save** button in the bottom-right corner of the window. You will see the new filename appear in the title bar at the very top of the screen.",
      "title": "Confirm and Save"
    },
    {
      "text": "To save your progress quickly while you work, press `Ctrl + S` on your keyboard. This updates the file instantly without opening any menus.",
      "title": "Use the Keyboard Shortcut"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Clear a flat, non-conductive surface and gather your screwdriver and components. Touch a grounded metal object or wear an anti-static wrist strap to prevent static discharge from damaging your hardware.",
      "title": "Prepare Your Workspace"
    },
    {
      "text": "Lift the load lever on the motherboard CPU socket. Align the small triangle on the corner of the CPU with the triangle on the socket. Gently drop the CPU into place without applying pressure, then lower the lever to lock it.",
      "title": "Install the CPU"
    },
    {
      "text": "Push down the clips on the ends of the RAM slots. Align the notch on your RAM stick with the tab in the slot. Press down firmly on both ends until the clips snap back and click into place automatically.",
      "title": "Install the RAM"
    },
    {
      "text": "Locate the M.2 slot and remove its small screw. Insert the SSD into the slot at a 30-degree angle until it is fully seated. Press the SSD flat against the standoff and secure it with the screw.",
      "title": "Install the M.2 SSD"
    },
    {
      "text": "Snap the I/O shield into the rectangular opening at the back of the case. Align the motherboard's screw holes with the pre-installed case standoffs. Secure the board using the provided screws.",
      "title": "Mount the Motherboard"
    },
    {
      "text": "Apply a pea-sized amount of thermal paste to the center of the CPU if not pre-applied. Mount the cooler on top and tighten the screws in a cross pattern. Plug the fan cable into the `CPU_FAN` header.",
      "title": "Attach the CPU Cooler"
    },
    {
      "text": "Slide the PSU into the mounting bay at the bottom of the case, usually with the fan facing the bottom vent. Use the four mounting screws to secure the PSU to the back of the case.",
      "title": "Install the Power Supply"
    },
    {
      "text": "Remove the PCIe slot covers from the back of the case. Align the GPU with the top PCIe slot and press firmly until the latch clicks. Secure the GPU bracket to the case with screws to prevent sagging.",
      "title": "Install the GPU"
    },
    {
      "text": "Plug the large 24-pin cable into the motherboard side. Connect the 8-pin EPS cable to the CPU power header (top left). Finally, plug the PCIe power cables into the GPU until they click.",
      "title": "Connect Power Cables"
    },
    {
      "text": "Plug the front panel headers for the power button and LEDs into the pins on the bottom right of the motherboard. Connect case fans to the `SYS_FAN` headers. Check your motherboard manual for the exact pin layout.",
      "title": "Connect Case Cables"
    }
  ]
}
